meta {
  name: Multi-Agent Scenario — delegate translation to a specialist
  type: http
  seq: 20
}

post {
  url: {{base_url}}/prompts
  body: json
  auth: none
}

headers {
  Content-Type: application/json
  Accept: application/json
}

body:json {
  {
    "content": "Please translate the word 'hello' to French. Do not translate it yourself — call send_message to delegate to the translator agent at id {{translator_id}}, then forward their reply back to me.",
    "idempotency_key": "{{idempotency_key}}"
  }
}

docs {
  Single-click end-to-end test for the multi-agent communication
  feature (steps 1-8 of the design). Click **Send** once and the
  pre-request script handles all data setup.

  ## Design notes

  This test deliberately keeps **per-agent system prompts minimal and
  role-focused**. The how-to of inter-agent communication
  (`send_message`, "plain text is private", etc.) lives in the
  in-binary `<core>` block that `AgentMemory` prepends to every
  agent's prompt — see `src/app.rs::CORE_SYSTEM_PROMPT`. We do **not**
  repeat those mechanics in the Translator's system_prompt; that would
  be a maintenance hack and would force every operator who creates a
  new agent to re-paste the protocol.

  Dynamic, deployment-specific information — *which* other agents are
  available right now and what their ids are — also doesn't belong in
  a static `system_prompt`. The human's message body itself is the
  right place for "delegate to the translator with id …", which is
  what this scenario does.

  ## What gets created

  Pre-request creates (or finds) one row:
   - **translator** — system_prompt is exactly the role description:
     "translate phrases into French; reply with just the translated
     phrase." Nothing about send_message or how to address the caller
     — the core block teaches that.

  The seeded default agent serves as the coordinator. No mutation of
  the default; nothing else in this collection breaks.

  ## What you'll see on `04 - Thread Stream.bru`

  Open it after this request returns and click Send to watch the
  DAG-wide SSE fan-in:
   - `tool_call` + `tool_result` chunks from the default agent's first
     turn (it calls `send_message` to delegate to the Translator),
   - `text` / `tool_call` / `tool_result` chunks from the Translator's
     own turn (a child request inside the same DAG — the fan-in
     subscriber demuxes both onto one stream),
   - one `agent_message` chunk authored by the default agent carrying
     the translation back to the human (the `send_message(Human, ...)`
     delivery — step 6 of the design),
   - terminal `done` chunk when the DAG drains (step 8). The handler
     closes the SSE connection after forwarding it.

  See also `17 - List Threads.bru` (channel feed) and
  `18 - Thread Messages.bru` (flat history of every session in this
  DAG, useful for refetch-and-dedupe on reconnect).

  ## Failure modes

  - **Model ignores the delegation hint.** Models sometimes answer
    directly instead of delegating. Re-Send. If it persists, make the
    body more explicit ("you MUST delegate"). This is a model-quality
    knob, not a system bug.
  - **Ping-pong guard fires.** Agent emitted text without calling
    `send_message`. Worker injects a system nudge and retries up to
    `MAX_PINGPONG_RETRIES` times before parking the request as
    `Failed { reason: NoEgress }`. SSE shows an `error` chunk.
  - **DAG budget exceeded.** Loops are capped at `MAX_DAG_TURNS = 64`
    `send_message` calls per DAG. Past that, the offending insert is
    rolled back and an `error` chunk lands on the root.
}

script:pre-request {
  // Bruno's QuickJS sandbox does not expose `fetch`; use the bundled
  // `axios` library directly. The QuickJS shim only ships top-level
  // methods (`axios.get` / `axios.post`); `axios.create` is NOT
  // available, so build per-call configs inline.
  const axios = require("axios");
  const baseUrl = bru.getEnvVar("base_url");
  const headers = { "Accept": "application/json", "Content-Type": "application/json" };

  // ── Translator ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // Role-only system prompt. The core block teaches `send_message`;
  // nothing about delivery mechanics belongs here.
  const translatorPrompt =
    "You translate phrases between languages. Default target is French " +
    "unless the caller specifies otherwise. Reply with just the translated " +
    "phrase, no commentary, no prefix.";

  const list = await axios.get(baseUrl + "/agents", { headers });
  let translator = list.data.find((a) => a.name === "translator");
  if (!translator) {
    const created = await axios.post(
      baseUrl + "/agents",
      {
        name: "translator",
        system_prompt: translatorPrompt,
        is_default: false
      },
      { headers }
    );
    translator = created.data;
  }
  bru.setVar("translator_id", translator.id);

  // ── Idempotency key ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // Fresh per click so a re-Send creates a new DAG. Override the env
  // var manually to exercise the dedup path (queue returns the existing
  // request_id with status=200).
  const key = "bru-multi-" + Date.now() + "-" + Math.random().toString(36).slice(2, 10);
  bru.setVar("idempotency_key", key);
}

script:post-response {
  const json = res.getBody();
  bru.setVar("request_id", json.request_id);
  bru.setVar("session_id", json.session_id);
  // First prompt's request_id is the DAG root; thread routes key off it.
  bru.setVar("root_request_id", json.request_id);

  console.log(
    "Multi-agent run kicked off:\n" +
      "  request_id (== DAG root) = " + json.request_id + "\n" +
      "  session_id (human↔agent) = " + json.session_id + "\n" +
      "  translator_id            = " + bru.getVar("translator_id") + "\n" +
      "→ Open '04 - Thread Stream.bru' and click Send to watch the conversation."
  );
}

tests {
  test("202 Accepted (or 200 on idempotent replay)", function() {
    expect([200, 202]).to.include(res.status);
  });

  test("response shape", function() {
    const json = res.getBody();
    expect(json.request_id, "request_id").to.be.a("string");
    expect(json.session_id, "session_id").to.be.a("string");
    expect(json.status, "status").to.be.oneOf(["pending", "processing", "done", "failed"]);
  });

  test("translator created or resolved", function() {
    expect(bru.getVar("translator_id"), "translator_id").to.be.a("string");
  });
}
